<p></p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=44826"><font color="#0000FF">View my Inventory</font></a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uuhrlik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uhrlik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#333333>(10/10/02 4:50:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fnamelesstavernfrm22.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=68.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Story of Uhrlik: Pain Remembers</span><hr size=1> The Story of Uhrlik:<br>
Pain Remembers<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The earth of Eastern Karana was drenched with the black stinking blood of the Teir’Dal. Their leader was a being so foul he oozed a corrupt and cancerous ichor from his wounds. It bubbled and foamed as it seeped from his body. Even after a bath and a thorough scrubbing of his armor, Uhrlik doubted that he would ever be free from the oily reek. He would never be washed clean, much like the land. Nothing new would ever grow where the wretched Dark Elf fell.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp After the fight with the Teir’Dal, the combined forces left the Plains of Karana. The feast was joined at the castle of Lore where the Knights welcomed their new friends the Feir’Dal and honored them with stories and food. The ale flowed freely and dishes from every corner of Norrath were served. The banquet lasted long into the night, most staggering upstairs to their appointed quarters, others choosing to sleep where their heads lay.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Eventually only the four at the lead table remained: the druids Nytte and Lamila and the warriors Iianae and Uhrlik. They spoke long and low about past adventures, about places they’d seen and people they’d met. Uhrlik felt a kinship with these two newfound friends, and before long he found that he was telling his own sordid history.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His telling was cold and dispassionate, but his eyes blazed with a bitterness and fury that belied his detached exterior. The warrior noticed that he rolled Anna’s ring through his fingers as he told his tale, and he shoved it firmly in his pouch and grasped his goblet with both hands.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Iianae followed him with her own story, her brow furrowed in disquieting symmetry. “I remember the orc war.” She started. Staring deep into her wine as if seeing it all again in some torturous mirror she continued, “My father, Iian, was guarding one of the lifts when the orcs attacked. I did everything I could to cut a path through to him, but I wasn’t strong enough. I just couldn’t get there fast enough.” Her voice dropped to nearly a whisper, “I lost him that night.” She drained her cup and pushed it away. Clearing her throat she looked deep in Uhrlik and Lamila’s eyes in turn. “I had no one after that, except for Master Regren.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik nodded into his own cup, remembering stalwart Master Regren, the head of the Emerald Warriors in Kelethin.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “What about your mother?” Lamila asked.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The warrioress turned a pained glance toward her, “My mother was taken by the orcs and made a slave. She…didn’t survive.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lamila gasped, “I’m so sorry.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Iianae shook her head, waving off the apology, “I don’t remember much of her, except that she used to sing a lot.” She smiled as she searched for a melody in her head.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik sighed heavily, “So many innocent people taken, so many forced to work to death.” He clenched his jaw tight for a moment and then spoke aloud almost to himself, “No, you can’t help them all. That’s a fight that we’ve all left to the next generation.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Suddenly the warrior’s head shot up, his eyes wide. He stared in utter disbelief across the table at Iianae. The unexpected movement shocked her to silence. Lamila and Nytte shifted their eyes between the two, unsure of what was wrong.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “What was that you were just singing?” Uhrlik asked rather insistently.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “The song that my mother used to sing to me, why?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Keep going. Sing on, please.” He urged.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The warrioress closed her eyes and a tiny smile crept across her lips. She began to sing softly, her voice rising slowly. A melody unlike any other echoed softly in the great hall. Clearly elven, the sound caressed the soul, comforting all but the most insidious hurts. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The mood of the lullaby changed abruptly as Uhrlik joined his own voice to it. It grew somehow. The bedtime tune became a symphony of emotion. It was dirge and lullaby all at the same time. It was glorious and simple, majestic and personal. Before this moment, each of the vocalists had gaps in their memories where the melody eluded them, but all gaps were filled in the presence of the other half of the song.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Something clicked in Uhrlik’s mind as the song ended, something his father had told him when he was little. His mother had lost her older sister to the orcish slave pens. His mother had never spoken much of her, preferring to keep the pain to herself. When she spoke of her childhood, however, she told how she and her sister would wander through the woods and sing. “She had such a glorious voice,” she would say. “Always singing, and so beautifully that Tunare herself could have cried.” Furtively, he shared the memory.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “So that would make us…cousins.” Iianae tumbled the word clumsily in her mouth, trying to get used to the feel of it.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lamila grasped Uhrlik’s hand underneath the table with one hand and wiped away her joyful tears with the other. She could feel how much it meant for Uhrlik to have family, real blood family, in the world.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The warrioress turned swiftly to face Nytte. “You know something more, don’t you?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Nytte said nothing, merely refilling his cup and shuffling his plate to the side.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Out with it, hon.” She urged. “We’ve known each other for too long for you to feel that you can’t tell me something.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He nodded and squeezed her hand lightly, “I know.” Though years never touched the elves it seemed that the fine lines around Nytte’s wizened eyes deepened with the effort of finding the words to a long buried memory.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp At length he began, “I too remember the orc war. I remember where it started, in the ignorance and complacency of the Council of Elder Druids.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “It started years before that horrible night. I was walking home late one night and I felt something…odd in the air. It was like a greasy slick crossed over my mind.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Dvinn.” Uhrlik snarled.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Nytte nodded. “I found out that the Dark Elves had sent their Ambassador to ally themselves with the Crushbone orcs, but I could not find out why. The minds of the Teir’Dal are a maze of traps and pitfalls even to themselves.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Being newly raised to the Council I waited with my petitions until they would hear me, but when they did, they scoffed at me. None of them had felt that shadow across their soul like I had. Even when presented with interrogation reports and testimonials of freed slaves they would not budge.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “So, after that warning I began to conduct my business in secret. I organized watches of druids and teams of rangers to scout the forest. Runners were set up in the cities of Faydwer to deliver messages and sound the alarm if an attack came.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Nytte lowered his head and spoke heavily, “Never had I dreamed the orcs would attack with such precision and force. That was my mistake. They came down from the hill and flanked the lift guards, swarming over them with sheer numbers. The watch sounded the alarm and the messengers ran. The druids began doing what they could to stem the tide of orcs, but there were so many and so well disciplined.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I watched as the platform guards leaped from the city into the midst of the blue wave and set to the slaughter. In the press of bodies and the stench of death I saw from my perch atop the city a single young woman, “ he looked deeply into Iianae’s eyes. “I made the decision that no matter what, this lady would survive the fight.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It almost seemed like Nytte’s eyes glassed over to match the tear rolling down Iianae’s cheek. He seemed to realize that he had been holding her hand the whole time and gave it another gentle squeeze.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “The next day we recovered the bodies of the fallen, including the rangers that I had sent to guard the woods. Their bodies were bloated with the poison from Dvinn’s black blade. The pyres were lit at sundown and raged on until morning. So many children were left with one or no parents at all. So many children sitting vigil with the fire that was once a loved one.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “By morning, most of the children had gone. Their guardians claimed them when physical and emotional exhaustion forced shut their eyelids. I watched over the grieving ones that remained, standing vigil with them and feeling their anguish as my own.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His eyes shifted from one to the next as he impressed his words on them, “I stood there, at a crossroads of my life, thinking. I stood for three days as two mourners sat nearly back to back and watched the ashes of their fathers drift away on the wind.” He looked to Uhrlik, “A young half elf boy with a short sword across his knees, burning with a dreadful vengeance,” The druid turned his eyes to Iianae, “and a graceful wood elven lady. Her mismatched armor was smeared with grime and soot and unheeded tears made tracks of clean across her smudged cheeks.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “At last I came to a decision. I felt a burning in my veins. An itching inside my head that could not be contained. So I marched to the Council chambers, interrupting a meeting of the Eldest. They were not happy to see me, but I berated them just the same. If they had listened to me years before that night could have been avoided. I resigned my position on the Council and stormed from their presence with a lighter heart.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “The burning in your veins you spoke of,” Lamila began, “The Wanderlust was in you, wasn’t it?”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Nytte nodded quickly, “Indeed it was. I spent years roaming across Norrath. But I believe that if that battle hadn’t occurred I would still be on the Council. It was my vigil with the mourners that awoke it in me. However dire the cost, I think that if I had not left, my dear friend Iianae and I might not have met up again, which is something that I’m rather grateful for.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Uhrlik cast a sidelong glance at Lamila, “Now I suppose you’ll tell me that you were there, too, in secret.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lamila laughed, “No, I missed that battle. I was exploring the ruined cities of Kunark when the orcs attacked.”<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp So the night wore on and the sun came up and the four talked as old friends renewing acquaintances…<br>
<br>
 <p>Uhrlik Mystblade<BR>
Officer, Guild Ambassador<BR>
and Champion
of Feir'Dal
